Polynomials and Splines Basis Functions

Alexandra Chronopoulou

Polynomial Basis

Representation of a function in terms of basis functions using a polynomial basis.

The following code created the plots the polynomial basis function up to order 4

x=seq(0, 1, by=0.001)
b0 = rep(1, length(x))
b1 = x
b2 = x^2
b3 = x^3
b4 = x^4

fun1 = 4*b0 -10* b1 + 16*b2 + 2*b3 -10*b4

par(mfrow = c(2,3))
plot(x, b0, type='l', lty=3, ylab=expression("b"[0]*"(x)=1"))
plot(x, b1, type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression("b"[1]*"(x)=x"))
plot(x, b2, type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression("b"[2]*"(x)=x"^2))
plot(x, b3, type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression("b"[3]*"(x)=x"^3))
plot(x, b4, type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression("b"[4]*"(x)=x"^4))
plot(x, fun1, type='l', ylab="f(x)", main=expression("f(x) =  4 - 10 x + 16 x"^2*"+ 2 x"^3*"- 10 x"^4), col="blue", lwd=2)

Cubic Splines Basis

We are going to start with the following basis as presented in the slides: \[\begin{align*} h_0(x) &= 1\\ h_1(x) &= x\\ h_{i+1}(x) &= R(x, \xi_i^*),\,\, i=1, \ldots, q-1 \end{align*}\] where \[\begin{align*} R(x,z) &= \left[ (z-1/2)^2 - 1/12\right] \left[ (x-1/2)^2 - 1/12\right]/4\\ & \quad \,- \left[ (|x-z|-1/2)^4 - 1/2 (|x-z|-1/2)^2 + 7/240\right] /24 \end{align*}\]

These basis functions are coded into R as follows:

## Cubic Splines

rk <- function(x,z){
  ((z-0.5)^2-1/12)*((x-0.5)^2-1/12)/4-((abs(x-z)-0.5)^4-(abs(x-z)-0.5)^2/2+7/240)/24
}

# Define the knots
new.knots= c(1/6, 3/6, 5/6)

# Determine an x 
# In regression examples this will be the predictor, there will be no need to generate x values.
x=seq(0, 1, by=0.01)
spline1 = rep(1, length(x)) # First basis function
spline2 = x # Second basis function
spline3 = rk(x,new.knots[1]) # Third basis function ...
spline4 = rk(x,new.knots[2])
spline5 = rk(x,new.knots[3])

#If we want to represent a function using the basis above, we have:
fun1s = 4*spline1 - 0.05*spline2 - 6*spline3 +2*spline4 +10*spline5

# We plot the basis functions defined above as well as the function:
par(mfrow = c(2,3))
plot(x, spline1, type='l', lty=3, ylab=expression("h"[0]*"(x)=1"))
plot(x, spline2, type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression("h"[1]*"(x)=x"))
plot(x, spline3, type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[2](x))*"="*paste(R(x,xi[1])))  )
plot(x, spline4, type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[3](x))*"="*paste(R(x,xi[2])))  )
plot(x, spline5, type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[4](x))*"="*paste(R(x,xi[3])))  )
plot(x, fun1s, type='l', ylab="f(x)", main=expression("f(x) =  4 - 0.05 h"[1]*" - 6 h"[2]*"+ 2 h"[3]*"+ 10 h"[4]), col="blue", lwd=2)

R B-splines

Now, let’s use the B-Splines functions from the splines library.

library(splines)

# Again, generate x values
x=seq(0, 1, by=0.01)
n=length(x)

# Define the knots 
new.knots= c(1/6, 3/6, 5/6)

# Create the B-Slines basis functions
Bsplines.basis = bs(x, knots=new.knots, intercept=TRUE)
dim(Bsplines.basis)
## [1] 101   7
head(Bsplines.basis)
##             1        2         3         4 5 6 7
## [1,] 1.000000 0.000000 0.0000000 0.0000000 0 0 0
## [2,] 0.830584 0.165912 0.0034896 0.0000144 0 0 0
## [3,] 0.681472 0.304896 0.0135168 0.0001152 0 0 0
## [4,] 0.551368 0.418824 0.0294192 0.0003888 0 0 0
## [5,] 0.438976 0.509568 0.0505344 0.0009216 0 0 0
## [6,] 0.343000 0.579000 0.0762000 0.0018000 0 0 0
par(mfrow = c(2,4))
plot(x, Bsplines.basis[,1], type='l', lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[0](x))))
plot(x, Bsplines.basis[,2], type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[1](x))))
plot(x, Bsplines.basis[,3], type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[2](x)) ))
plot(x, Bsplines.basis[,4], type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[3](x))))

plot(x, Bsplines.basis[,7], type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[6](x))))

R Natural Cubic Splines (NCS)

These area again in the splines library. So…

NCS.basis =ns(x, knots=new.knots, Boundary.knots=c(0,1), intercept=TRUE)
dim(NCS.basis)
## [1] 101   5
par(mfrow = c(2,3))
plot(x, NCS.basis[,1], type='l', lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[0](x))))
plot(x, NCS.basis[,2], type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[1](x))))
plot(x, NCS.basis[,3], type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[2](x)) ))
plot(x, NCS.basis[,4], type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[3](x))))
plot(x, NCS.basis[,5], type='l',lty=3, ylab=expression(paste(h[4](x))))
